05090nam a22008415i 9780674419278DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20132001mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806744192787 a10.4159/harvard.97806744192782doi  a(DE-B1597)252806  a(OCoLC)979576139  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aKF8742 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a347.73/2621 aFallon, Jr., Richard H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImplementing the Constitution /cRichard H. Fallon, Jr.  aReprint 2014 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2013] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (186 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: The Supreme Court’s Disputed Role -- tCHAPTER 1. Originalism -- tCHAPTER 2. The Supreme Court as the Forum of Principle -- tCHAPTER 3. Constitutional Implementation -- tCHAPTER 4. Extraordinary Adjudication -- tCHAPTER 5. Doctrinal Tests and the Constitution -- tCHAPTER 6. Ordinary Adjudication -- tCHAPTER 7. Legitimacy and the Unwritten Constitution -- tCHAPTER 8. Against Populism and Methodological Pragmatism -- tConclusion: Beyond History and Philosophy -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book argues that the Supreme Court performs two functions. The first is to identify the Constitution's idealized "meaning." The second is to develop tests and doctrines to realize that meaning in practice. Bridging the gap between the two--implementing the Constitution--requires moral vision, but also practical wisdom and common sense, ingenuity, and occasionally a willingness to make compromises. In emphasizing the Court's responsibility to make practical judgments, Implementing the Constitution takes issue with the two positions that have dominated recent debates about the Court's proper role. Constitutional "originalists" maintain that the Court's essential function is to identify the "original understanding" of constitutional language and then apply it deductively to current problems. This position is both unwise and unworkable, the book argues. It also critiques well-known accounts according to which the Court is concerned almost exclusively with matters of moral and constitutional principle. Implementing the Constitution bridges the worlds of constitutional theory, political theory, and constitutional practice. It illuminates the Supreme Court's decision of actual cases and its development of well-known doctrines. It is a doctrinal study that yields jurisprudential insights and a contribution to constitutional theory that is closely tied to actual judicial practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aConstitutional law. 0aRecht. 4aConstitutional law -- United States. 4aLAW / General. 4aUnited States. Supreme Court. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Law & Political Science eBook Packagez9783110353495oZDB-23-HLP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831104422050 cprintz978067441926140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067441927840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674419278423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674419278/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACK